author: @mohammednadhim1918
text: on 38:00 he was  wrong   here is the answer according to google bard  The image you sent shows two normal distributions. The distribution on the top has a higher variance than the distribution on the bottom. This is because the distribution on the top is wider and more spread out than the distribution on the bottom.  Variance is a measure of how spread out a distribution is. It is the average squared distance of all data points from the mean of the distribution. A higher variance means that the data points are further away from the mean, on average.  In the image, the distribution on the top has a wider spread of data points than the distribution on the bottom. This means that the data points in the left distribution are further away from the mean, on average, than the data points in the right distribution. Therefore, the distribution on the top has a higher variance.

author: @tejeshivsn632
text: Homework: why do we use n-1 is used in the formula for calculating sample variance instead of n?  To answer this let us understand the difference between the sample mean and population mean. Population mean is the average computed for the entire data and sample mean is the average computed for that particular sample. Therefore there would be some differences between them. the sample mean will be close to the population mean.   Now coming to sample variance and population variance, the difference will be huge between the sum of the squares of the difference between data and sample mean and the sum of squares of (data - population mean). This is due to the small difference between the sample mean and population mean. When it is squared the difference is more. To compensate for the difference we use n-1 in the denominator to increase the value such that the sample variance is closer to the population variance. Why n-1 the value comes closer when we compute considering n-1 than to n-2, n-3, and others.   Happy learning!!

text: While finding percentile we used to use this formula if r = np is integer , then use r if r = np is not an integer, then use [r+1] ,  and select the integer part  say u have to find 25 percentile  and u have say 10 observations so arrange the n obsn in ascending order . n = 10 , p = 25/100 = 0.25 so r = np = 2.5  is not an integer,  so we take [2.5+1] = [3.5] and integer part of [3.5] is 3.   so the 25 percentile is the 3 observation.
